    linkedDinoDexSpecies: ["ichthyosaurus", "plesiosaurus"],
    image: "images/fossil_hunters/mary_anning.jpg",
    imageAlt: "Mary Anning, fossil collector and preparator",
    imageCaption: "Mary Anning (1799–1847)",
    imageFit: "cover",
    imagePosition: "center top",
    modal: {
      person: `Mary Anning was born in 1799 in Lyme Regis, Dorset, into a family of Protestant dissenters too poor to educate her formally. Her father, a cabinetmaker, took her fossil-hunting along the Blue Lias cliffs from an early age. When he died in 1810, she and her brother Joseph began selling fossils to tourists and collectors to keep the family fed. She taught herself geology and comparative anatomy from borrowed books and the specimens she extracted from the rock herself. She corresponded with the leading geologists of her day, identified coprolites as fossilised faeces, and corrected their interpretations more than once. She died from breast cancer in 1847, still in financial difficulty, still not a member of the Geological Society of London, which did not admit women until 1904.`,
      discovery: `In 1811–12, the Anning siblings uncovered the first ichthyosaur to be scientifically described - a creature that looked like nothing living. In 1823, Anning found the first near-complete plesiosaur, so strange that Georges Cuvier initially suspected it was a hoax. In 1828 she uncovered the first pterosaur found outside Germany. These were not isolated lucky finds: Anning made her living by reading the rock systematically, understanding erosion patterns, and knowing precisely where and when to look. Her specimens ended up in the collections of the British Museum, the Natural History Museum, and institutions across Europe - usually without her name attached.`,
      ideaChanged: `Before Anning's discoveries, the prevailing view was that God's creation was complete and permanent - no species had ever gone extinct. The creatures she pulled from the cliffs were manifestly not alive anywhere on Earth. They forced natural philosophers to seriously engage with the idea of extinction and with the enormous timescale of life on Earth. Her ichthyosaur and plesiosaur specimens were among the primary physical exhibits that destabilised the biblical account of natural history and cleared the ground for evolutionary thinking. In this sense, Anning's fossils helped make Darwin's argument possible, even though she died twelve years before the Origin of Species.`,
      messyBit: `The Anning story risks two kinds of distortion. The first is straightforward injustice: she was routinely uncredited by the male scientists who published papers about her finds. William Buckland, William Conybeare, Henry De la Beche and others described her specimens as if they had identified them themselves. De la Beche did raise money for her through a painting based on her finds, but financial generosity and intellectual credit are different things. The second risk is hagiographic overcorrection: recent waves of commemoration can flatten a complex figure into a simple martyr narrative. She was also a skilled, sharp-minded scientist who built relationships with the Geological Society's members strategically and knew exactly what her fossils were worth, scientifically and financially.`,
      legacyInDinodex: `Every marine reptile entry in DinoDex - Ichthyosaurus, Plesiosaurus, and the larger marine section - traces its visible history to Anning's cliffs. The "Evidence in the Rock" philosophy of DinoDex - separating what is directly preserved from what is inferred - reflects precisely the kind of rigorous reading of rock and bone that Anning practised without institutional support or formal training.`
    },
