    imageFit: "cover",
    imagePosition: "center top",
    modal: {
      person: `Richard Owen was born in Lancaster in 1804 and trained as a surgeon before becoming a comparative anatomist of extraordinary ability and productivity. He was appointed Hunterian Professor at the Royal College of Surgeons, then superintendent of the natural history collections at the British Museum, where he campaigned for decades for a separate institution devoted to natural history. When the Natural History Museum opened in South Kensington in 1881, it embodied his vision - grand, Gothic, and deliberately cathedral-like. He was fêted by the establishment, tutored the royal children in science, and received a knighthood. He was also, by multiple accounts, capable of professional ruthlessness toward scientific rivals. Thomas Henry Huxley considered him a deeply unreliable colleague.`,
      discovery: `Owen's signal contribution was not a field discovery but a synthesis. In 1842, having studied fragmentary fossils of Megalosaurus, Iguanodon, and Hylaeosaurus described by others, he recognised that these three animals shared a suite of anatomical features - fully erect limb posture, fused sacral vertebrae, advanced proportions - that set them apart from all known living and fossil reptiles. He proposed the group name Dinosauria. He also conceived and oversaw the Crystal Palace dinosaur sculptures of 1854, the first life-size public representations of prehistoric animals - and famously hosted a dinner for scientific guests inside the mould of the Iguanodon before it was finished.`,
      ideaChanged: `Owen's invention of Dinosauria is one of the most consequential acts of classification in science history, though he got key things wrong. He imagined dinosaurs as warm, upright, and mammal-like - not because he was ahead of his time but because he wanted them to refute evolutionary progressionism. He was specifically anti-Darwinian, and his 'superior' dinosaurs were meant to show that the past was no simpler than the present, undermining the idea of evolution from lower to higher forms. The irony is that his description of active, erect dinosaurs was overturned in the early 20th century, then partially rehabilitated again by the Dinosaur Renaissance - but for entirely different, evidence-based reasons.`,
      messyBit: `Owen was removed from the councils of the Royal Society after a formal inquiry found he had dishonestly claimed credit for work done by a subordinate. His treatment of Gideon Mantell - including a widely condemned obituary - was a low point even by Victorian scientific standards. He was a fierce opponent of Darwin and Huxley, and his opposition to evolution became increasingly untenable as the evidence accumulated. His anti-evolutionary position, combined with his institutional power, arguably delayed British acceptance of the dinosaur-bird connection for decades.`,
      legacyInDinodex: `Owen sits at the origin of the site's entire subject matter: without his 1842 grouping, there are no 'dinosaurs' to discuss. But he also exemplifies the institution-building side of palaeontology - the Natural History Museum, which holds specimens from Archaeopteryx to Iguanodon, is his direct creation. And his complex, contradictory personality is a useful corrective to hagiographic science history: the man who named dinosaurs was also, demonstrably, someone most scientists of his era found professionally difficult.`
    },
