    image: "images/fossil_hunters/barnum_brown.jpg",
    imageAlt: "Barnum Brown, field palaeontologist and collector",
    imageCaption: "Barnum Brown (1873–1963)",
    imageFit: "contain",
    imagePosition: "center",
    modal: {
      person: `Barnum Brown was born in 1873 in Carbondale, Kansas, and named - against all odds - after P.T. Barnum. He grew up collecting fossil shells from ploughed fields and studied under vertebrate palaeontologist Samuel Williston before joining the American Museum of Natural History in 1897, where he would remain, in various capacities, until 1963. He was known for wearing a fur coat in the field, for charm that got him access to private lands across four continents, and - according to a documented account in the American Museum's records - for occasionally supplying information to American agencies during his overseas expeditions. He never completed his doctoral thesis. He wrote almost no scientific papers. He found more significant fossil material than nearly anyone before or since.`,
      discovery: `In the summer of 1902, digging in Hell Creek, Montana, Brown found the first documented partial skeleton of Tyrannosaurus rex. Six years later he found the better-preserved specimen that became the centrepiece of the AMNH's dinosaur hall. He also collected major specimens of Ankylosaurus (which he named), Corythosaurus, and many others from the Red Deer River in Alberta - using a flat-bottomed barge as a field camp, arguably the most elegant logistical solution in the history of fossil collecting.`,
      ideaChanged: `Brown's contribution was less conceptual than infrastructural. By building the AMNH collection into a global resource, he created the physical basis for twentieth-century vertebrate palaeontology. The specimens he collected have been re-studied repeatedly as new methods became available: bone histology on his Hell Creek T. rex material, CT scanning on specimens he brought back from India and Burma. He showed that a dedicated field collector, working systematically over decades, could transform what a science knows simply by finding more of it.`,
      messyBit: `Brown received almost none of the scientific credit for T. rex during his lifetime. Henry Fairfield Osborn, the AMNH president who formally described and named the animal, was credited in contemporary accounts as the discoverer - a misrepresentation that Brown reportedly accepted without visible protest. He collected from multiple countries under conditions that would now be considered problematic - acquiring specimens without formal agreements, exploiting local knowledge without crediting or compensating its sources.`,
      legacyInDinodex: `Tyrannosaurus rex in DinoDex carries the full weight of what Brown found - the most studied predator in the fossil record, whose growth rates, bite force, and senses are known in remarkable detail. That depth of knowledge is possible because Brown found two good skeletons, and the AMNH kept them and made them available. The gap between Brown's field genius and his public recognition is also quietly embedded in DinoDex's philosophy: the fossils tell the story; the names attached to their discovery are often an accident of institutional power.`
    },
