    image: "images/fossil_hunters/jose_bonaparte.jpg",
    imageAlt: "José Bonaparte, vertebrate palaeontologist",
    imageCaption: "José Bonaparte (1928–2020)",
    imageFit: "cover",
    imagePosition: "center top",
    modal: {
      person: `José Fernando Bonaparte was born in Buenos Aires in 1928 and largely taught himself palaeontology through self-education and fieldwork over decades when Argentina had almost no academic palaeontology infrastructure. He worked at the Miguel Lillo Foundation in Tucumán and later at the Museo Argentino de Ciencias Naturales in Buenos Aires. He conducted fieldwork across Patagonia, the Andes, and Brazil from the 1960s through the 1990s, discovering fossil beds that were essentially unknown to international science. He trained the next generation of Argentine palaeontologists - Fernando Novas, Rodolfo Coria, and others either worked with him directly or were inspired by his example - and effectively established Argentine vertebrate palaeontology as a functioning discipline. He died in 2020.`,
      discovery: `Bonaparte named Carnotaurus sastrei in 1985 - one of the most anatomically distinct large theropods ever found, with bull-like horns, a deep skull, and dramatically reduced forelimbs - from Patagonia. He described Abelisaurus, Noasaurus, Amargasaurus, and Mussaurus, the last of which (a sauropodomorph from Triassic Argentina) he first described from hatchlings so tiny they were initially mistaken for embryos. He also contributed to the discovery of early dinosaur material from the Ischigualasto Formation that would later yield Eoraptor and Herrerasaurus to international teams. Over decades he demonstrated that South American dinosaurs were not simply southern extensions of Northern Hemisphere lineages but represented separately evolved groups with their own anatomical signatures.`,
      ideaChanged: `Before Bonaparte, palaeontology was effectively a Northern Hemisphere enterprise. The dinosaurs that stocked museums and textbooks - Tyrannosaurus, Stegosaurus, Diplodocus - came overwhelmingly from North America and Europe, and the implicit assumption was that these were broadly representative of dinosaur evolution. Bonaparte's decades of work demonstrated that Gondwana - the southern supercontinent - carried its own radiation of dinosaurs, the abelisaurids and titanosaurs and early sauropodomorphs, that were not just southern versions of northern forms but genuinely distinct evolutionary lineages shaped by geographic isolation. This geographical reframing of palaeontology - from a Northern Hemisphere discipline to a global science - continues with every new find from Africa, Madagascar, India, and Antarctica.`,
      messyBit: `Bonaparte's career unfolded under political conditions that science rarely acknowledges directly: he did his most significant work during and in the aftermath of Argentina's military dictatorship of 1976–1983, in a country where academic institutions were severely disrupted and international collaboration was complicated by limited resources and political instability. The global reach his finds eventually achieved came partly because he was willing to work with international collaborators, and partly because Argentine geology had been largely overlooked by the English-speaking scientific establishment for so long that his finds were genuinely novel to the international community. His limited access to the major journals and conferences that European and North American scientists took for granted meant his work took longer to fully register in the literature than it deserved.`,
      legacyInDinodex: `Carnotaurus in DinoDex carries the full weight of what Southern Hemisphere palaeontology discovered: a predator so anatomically extreme - horns, vestigial arms, deep skull, racing-body proportions - that it forced a fundamental revision of what abelisaurid theropods could do and be. Argentinosaurus, the largest land animal in the DinoDex, emerged from the Patagonian beds that Bonaparte was among the first to systematically investigate. Together, they stand for the global nature of the story DinoDex tells - a story that would have remained half-told if palaeontology had stayed in the Northern Hemisphere.`
    },
